{
  "texts": [
    "Figure 2:2Figure2: The driver and the checker in a TB, assuming the DUT has two input ports \"a\" and \"b\" and one output port \"c\".",
    "Figure 3:3Figure 3: AutoBench: The TB generation workflow in detail.the problem description and module header, the LLM is guided to directly generate the RTL code for DUT at stage 0.",
    "Because the generated RTL is only used for the discriminator in the next step, the correctness of the generated code does not have to be very high as long as there are sufficient features for the later discrimination.",
    "As the Verilog syntax is strictly restricted by IEEE standard[1], the circuit type of an RTL code can be simply determined by special code statements using a Python script.",
    "For example, consider a simple instance of always@(posedge signalx), where \"signalx\" represents any signal."
  ]
}